4.41/5  rDev -2.6%look: 4 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4.5Draft at pies&pints; nonic pint. (Re-reviewed 7-27-16, bottle dated 7-19-16!)
Appearance: clear pale orange with 1 finger (3 fingers) bright white (just off-white) head. Little visible carb, not much retention (excellent retention of 1/8 inch of foam) Very nice lacing.
Aroma: tropical and resin; nothing distinct, but more potent than white rajah or sculpin.  (Peach, grapefruit, mango, pineapple, kumquat, light white bread hint of sweetness)
Taste: light tart arrival, bold hoppy citrus mid-palate; incredibly light and fresh. Bitter finish, but cleans up really quickly; little residual bitterness. (Immediate hoppy grapefruit, citrus, and resinous arrival with a tough more of a crackery malt than I remembered on draft. On mid palate the hops keep coming on strong, but are balanced by a hint of malty sweetness. There is a lingering, pleasant and citric bitterness on the finish).
Mouthfeel: light to mid bodied; little (moderate) carb; clean as can be, with no astringency.
Overall: perhaps the world's best "patio beer." Hoppier than any pale I've ever had and most IPAs, but hoppiness does not linger. Kind of like an IPL. A lot like southern tier live. Would drink this everyday May to September if possible. (Still true, but in a word: finesse. This beer is bold without being overpowering. That is a tremendous balancing act and this executes perfectly. I'd call it an IPA, though.) 1,400 charactersSaltofOH, Aug 01, 2015
