4.78/5  rDev +5.5%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 5 | feel: 4.75 |  overall: 4.75I just left 3 Floyd's and ZD did not disappoint. The line for carry outs was huge because they were selling ZD by the case. I should have grabbed some but little room in my suit case back to Florida. The beer on tap was superb!
A- The appearance looks like your typical pale ale but has excellent lacing from start to finish.
S - Smells like you would expect. Grapefruit, and a little pine.
T- The balance is perfect.  The IBU's are just right with the malt. I know a lot of people say ZD should be considered an IPA but if it were any more bitter it would dominate the beer. I think it is just bordering into IPA Land.  Grapefruit is definitely tasted but I also pick up a little orange flavor that has just the right amount of sweetness not to be cloying.
M - The beer goes down so smoothly. Definitely the most easily drinkable PA I've ever had.  You don't even think about the carbonation because it's perfect. I was anticipating a very drinkable beer and I was more than satisfied.
O - It was even better than expected. I know there is a lot of hype surrounding this pale ale but sitting in the tap room after having 2 pints of this beer all I can say is I loved it!  How much do I love it?  Let's just say that if I was alone on a desert island and a case of cold beer washed up onto the shore I would want it to be this beer.  There is a reason this beer is rated so damn high!
It's been a couple years since I wrote this review.  I've since travelled all over California and Vermont trying every PA/IPA I could get my hands on, as well as drinking some great IPAs in Florida.  Guess what?  I would still pick ZD for that desert island.
Just left FFF once again and I have to say that Permanent Funeral is even better than ZD. 1,740 charactersELS, Aug 07, 2014
