S- Holy hell. All citrus. Oh my goodness this is just incredible. I want a million air fresheners of this scent with me at all times. It is just so prounounced and crisp I can't get over that this might be the best smelling beer I have had to date. If you can think of a citrusy fruit- that fruit is in this aroma!
T/M- This is where I cry; in a good way. I almost had an emotional breakdown when this beer first touched my lips. Again, this beer is all citrus/all the time. Orange/Tangerine and pineapple take the forefront but backed up by a complexity of other fruits associated with Citra hops. There is also a nice tiny sweetness that plays peek-a-boo on your palate that is some sort of a gumball-y flavor. Its nice to get a malt presence in a beer that isn't the same old caramel/toffee/biscuit. IBUs on the high said for an APA, but I like it like that. Balance is spot on and mouthfeel is great. Nice medium body and moderate carbonation with a decently dry finish make this an awesome and refreshing beer.
O- Seriously, this is the best APA I have had to date and I don't know if it can get much better. I also had the 3Kings on this trip to the pub and though that was also an A beer, this one just rocks; its unreal. I ended up buying a growler to go of both ZD and 3Kings because these APAs made me have an out of body experience. Thank you FFF for creating Zombie Dust... 1,586 charactersTheGordianKnot, May 03, 2011
4.2/5  rDev -7.3%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4 | feel: 4.5 |  overall: 4Enjoyed from the tap at the Three Floyds brewpub, poured inside a nonic pint.
Very hazy honey color, with only a shadow of a finger visible behind. A fluffy, one-finger head of pure white sits atop, and great sticky walls of bubbles grip the sides as I descend through the glass. 
Crazy-good citrus hop aroma. Incredible, actually. Pine, grass, dank weed, onions, honey, crackers and a light earthiness.
Not as bitingly hoppy as nose would suggest. Fresh grass, onions, hints of citrus and honey. Pale cracker malt sweeps in at the clean, crisp finish. Very hoppy for a pale ale, but the balance never gets out of whack. 
Lightly prickly carbonation, amidst a hefty, silky-smooth medium body. Alcohol numbs the tongue just a bit, as do hints of micro-bubbled fizz. Crisp, clean finish keeps you coming back for more, and quickly. 
I hope Three Floyds does what everyone around me was suggesting and puts this on their regular rotation. Incredible complexity for a single hop IPA. Citrus hops are much more versatile than I thought. 1,036 charactersPhelps, May 02, 2011
