4.45/5  rDev -1.8%look: 4.5 | smell: 4.5 | taste: 4.5 | feel: 4 |  overall: 4.5Mmmmm...Ciiiittrrrraaa!
On tap at Three Floyds on the day before Dark Lord Day. Served in an imperial pint.
Appearance
A glowing apricot orange with a very dense head, the consistency of cask ale pumped through a sparkler tip. Lots of heavy lacing.
Aroma
The nose is bombed by pineapple fruit. Grapefruit comes in to round it out with a little bit of a rind-like bitterness. But in all its a sweeter smelling beer, concentrated with hops. 
Taste
Very in line with the nose, in that there is a huge burst of pineapple, edged with grapefruit. Very juicy and tropical. This is how I like my hoppy beers. Peripherals of mango, peach and orange build the juicy body of this beer. I'm not totally convinced this is an APA, but its too good to make any arguments that are that meaningless. 
Mouthfeel
Drrryyy, dry-dry. It gives this beer a nice abrupt, cleansing finish that keeps this beer going down quickly. Even though the alcohol is high for the style it makes not much of a showing. 
Overall
A tropical fruit, pineapple bomb, and I love it. I can't wait for this to find its way into bottles. When it does I will be making some trades. 1,140 charactersMbpBugeye, May 02, 2011
